from scipy import stats

# Define the number of samples

    return np.random.normal(loc=mean, scale=np.sqrt(variance), size=size)

    return [v for v in values if lower <= v <= upper]

        initial_data[key] = adjust_to_quantiles(initial_data[key], q10, q90)

    for i in range(len(features)):
        for j in range(i+1, len(features)):
            # This is a placeholder to simulate adjustments based on correlation; actual implementation would involve more sophisticated statistical methods or machine learning models
            if corr_type == 'pearson':

                data[features[j]] = np.interp(stats.ranks(data[features[i]]), stats.ranks(np.quantile(data[features[j]], q=[0.1, 0.5, 0.9]))

    min_val = np.min(initial_data[key])
    max_val = np.max(initial_data[key])
    initial_data[key] = adjust_to_quantiles(initial_data[key], 0.1, 0.9) # This is a placeholder for more complex covariance enforcement logic

# Ensure the generated data points respect given correlations and quantiles (again, this is highly simplified; actual implementation would be significantly more nuanced)
ensure_correlation(initial_data, 'pearson')  # Assuming Pearson correlation to start with due to its stronger linear relationship assumption

            initial_data[key] = adjusted_values
    return initial_data

# Perform recursive criticism to refine the data points
